<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="sec-u2-null-space-image-space">
  <title>Null space and image space</title>

  <p>
    The following important examples are representative of two canonical ways of describing a subspace.
  </p>

  <p>
    From here on, homogeneous equations play a special role. To solve <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m> by row reduction, we could write the augmented matrix <m>[A\mid \mathbf{0}]</m>. Since the right-hand side stays zero throughout the row operations, the coefficient matrix <m>A</m> carries the essential information.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-5-1-null-and-image-space-of-matrix">
    <title>Null Space and Image Space</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix. The <term>null space</term> of <m>A</m>, denoted <m>\nulls(A)</m>, is the set of vectors <m>\mathbf{x}</m> in <m>\R^n</m> which are solutions to the equation <m>A \mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}</m>, i.e.,
        <me>\nulls(A) = \{ \mathbf{x} \in \R^n : A \mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0} \}</me>.
        The <term>image space</term> of <m>A</m>, denoted <m>\im(A)</m>, is the set of vectors <m>\mathbf{y}</m> in <m>\R^m</m> such that <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{y}</m> has a solution, i.e.,
        <me>\im(A) = \{ A\mathbf{x} : \mathbf{x} \in \R^n \}</me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <note xml:id="note-u2-null-image-input-output">
    <p>
      The null space lives in the input space. It records input directions that <m>A</m> sends to <m>\mathbf{0}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The image space lives in the output space. It records outputs that <m>A</m> can reach.
    </p>
  </note>

  <table xml:id="tab-u2-null-image-locations">
    <tabular>
      <row header="yes"><cell>Object</cell><cell>Lives in</cell><cell>How to read it</cell></row>
      <row><cell><m>\operatorname{null}(A)</m></cell><cell><m>\mathbb R^n</m></cell><cell>input directions <m>A</m> forgets</cell></row>
      <row><cell><m>\operatorname{im}(A)</m></cell><cell><m>\mathbb R^m</m></cell><cell>outputs <m>A</m> can reach</cell></row>
    </tabular>
  </table>

  <activity xml:id="u2-act-revisit-height-subspaces">
    <title>Revisiting the height map with subspace language</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Return to <xref ref="u2-act-preview-forgets-depth"/>. Let
        <me>
          P=
          \begin{bmatrix}
          1&amp;0&amp;0\\
          0&amp;1&amp;0
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
        Describe the output subspace and the subspace of input directions that <m>P</m> forgets.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        For
        <me>
          \mathbf{x}
          =
          \begin{bmatrix}
          x\\
          y\\
          z
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          P\mathbf{x}
          =
          \begin{bmatrix}
          x\\
          y
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        As <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> vary freely, every vector in <m>\mathbb R^2</m> occurs as an output.
        Therefore
        <me>
          \operatorname{im}(P)=\mathbb R^2.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        The directions that <m>P</m> forgets are the solutions to <m>P\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m>. This requires
        <me>
          x=0,\qquad y=0,
        </me>
        while <m>z</m> is free. Thus
        <me>
          \operatorname{null}(P)
          =
          \left\{
          \begin{bmatrix}
          0\\
          0\\
          t
          \end{bmatrix}
          :
          t\in\mathbb R
          \right\}.
        </me>
        This subspace records the height direction.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </activity>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-5-1-null-space-is-a-space">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For any <m>m \times n</m> matrix, the null space of <m>A</m> is a subspace of <m>\R^n</m>, and the image space of <m>A</m> is a subspace of <m>\R^m</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        We start by showing the null space of <m>A</m> is a subspace. Recall the properties discussed in <xref ref="thm-2-2-distributive-properties"/>:
        <dl>
          <li>
            <title>Contains the zero vector</title>
            <p><m>\mathbf{0} \in \nulls(A)</m> because <m>\mathbf{A} \mathbf{0} = \mathbf{0}</m>.</p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Closure under addition</title>
            <p>
              Suppose <m>\mathbf{v} \in \nulls(A)</m> and <m>\mathbf{w} \in \nulls(A)</m>. Then <m>A \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}</m> and <m>A \mathbf{w} = \mathbf{0}</m>. So
              <me>A (\mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w}) = A \mathbf{v} + A \mathbf{w} = \mathbf{0} + \mathbf{0} = \mathbf{0}</me>.
              Thus <m>\mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w} \in \nulls(A)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Closure under scalar multiplication</title>
            <p>
              If <m>\mathbf{v} \in \nulls(A)</m>, and <m>a</m> is a scalar, then
              <me>A(a \mathbf{v}) = a (A \mathbf{v}) = a \mathbf{0} = \mathbf{0} </me>.
              Thus <m>a \mathbf{v} \in \nulls(A)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </dl>
        So <m>\nulls(A)</m> is a subspace of <m>\R^n</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Next, we show that <m>\im(A)</m> is a subspace.
        <dl>
          <li>
            <title>Contains the zero vector</title>
            <p><m>\mathbf{0} \in \im(A)</m> because <m>\mathbf{A} \mathbf{0} = \mathbf{0}</m>.</p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Closure under addition</title>
            <p>
              Suppose <m>\mathbf{v} \in \im(A)</m> and <m>\mathbf{w} \in \im(A)</m>. Then the equations <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{v}</m> and <m>A \mathbf{x} = \mathbf{w}</m> both have solutions, i.e., there exists <m>\mathbf{x}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{x}_2</m> such that <m>A\mathbf{x}_1 = \mathbf{v}</m> and <m>A\mathbf{x}_2 = \mathbf{w}</m>. Then
              <me>A(\mathbf{x}_1 + \mathbf{x}_2) = A\mathbf{x}_1 + A\mathbf{x}_2 = \mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w}</me>,
              so the equation <m>A \mathbf{x} = \mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w}</m> has a solution, and so <m>\mathbf{v} + \mathbf{w} \in \im(A)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>Closure under scalar multiplication</title>
            <p>
              If <m>\mathbf{v} \in \im(A)</m>, and <m>a</m> is a scalar, then we may write <m>\mathbf{v} = A\mathbf{x}_1</m> for some <m>\mathbf{x}_1</m>. But then
              <me>A(a\mathbf{x}_1) = a (A\mathbf{x}_1) = a \mathbf{v}</me>,
              so the equation <m>A\mathbf{x} = a \mathbf{v}</m> has a solution, so that <m>a \mathbf{v} \in \im(A)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </dl>
        Thus <m>\im(A)</m> is a subspace of <m>\R^m</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <warning xml:id="warn-u2-homogeneous-vs-nonhomogeneous-subspaces">
    <p>
      The solution set of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}</m> is a subspace. The solution set of <m>A\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{b}</m> for <m>\mathbf{b}\neq\mathbf{0}</m> is usually not a subspace; when it is nonempty, it is a shifted copy of <m>\nulls(A)</m>.
    </p>
  </warning>

</subsection>
